width: 262.80px; height: 49.20px;"><img alt="page1image408" src="images/image16.png" style="width: 262.80px; height: 49.20px; margin-left: -0.00px; margin-top: -0.00px; transform: rotate(0.00rad) translateZ(0px); -webkit-transform: rotate(0.00rad) translateZ(0px);" title=""></span></p></div><p class="c0"><span class="c3">&nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; </span></p><p class="c0"><span class="c14">BA Fine Art Camberwell 2023/24</span></p><p class="c0"><span class="c14">Artwork PDF: Unit 10 Element 1, Practice and Articulation</span></p><p class="c0 c2"><span class="c34 c37"></span></p><p class="c0"><span class="c45 c40">Student Name: </span><span class="c30">Natalia Romero Gutierrez </span><span class="c40 c45">&nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp;Course: </span><span class="c30 c34 c39">BA Fine Art Painting (with Creative Computing)</span></p><p class="c0 c2"><span class="c10"></span></p><p class="c0"><span class="c14">Below is my 300-word artist statement as well as 12-20 images of my practical work forming my full submission. </span></p><p class="c0 c2"><span class="c10"></span></p><p class="c0"><span class="c5">300 Word Artist Statement</span></p><p class="c0 c2"><span class="c10"></span></p><p class="c0 c2"><span class="c10"></span></p><a id="t.184c3276dc1108d0b37b5b394a2b32f732964a16"></a><a id="t.0"></a><table class="c56"><tr class="c58"><td class="c54" colspan="1" rowspan="1"><p class="c15"><span class="c9">Natalia Guti&eacute;rrez, originally from Tulu&aacute;, an emerging town in Colombia, is a queer painter whose art is a deeply biographical exploration of her life and experiences. By growing up in Colombia, moving to Spain at the age of eight, and relocating to the UK four years ago, &nbsp;she is still learning the complexities of migration now, as an adult. Natalia&rsquo;s journey is marked by migration, cultural displacement, and the continuous redefinition of home. </span></p><p class="c15"><span class="c9">Her paintings are rooted in memories and old family photographs, creating vivid scenes and conversations about sexuality, faith, and the struggles of displacement. Each piece is a narrative that bridges her personal history with broader themes of identity and belonging. Currently graduating from Fine Art Painting and Creative Computing at Camberwell College of Arts, Natalia combines traditional and digital techniques, preparing final compositions in oils on canvas. This fusion of methods reflects her dynamic approach to art, blending innovation with classical mediums.</span></p><p class="c15"><span class="c9">Her live-paintings focus on people of color and queer individuals, providing visibility and appreciation to those traditionally underrepresented in classical art. Natalia&#39;s commitment to diversity and representation contributes to the broader conversation on inclusion in the art world, making her work a powerful statement of the right to simply exist, belong, and be seen. &nbsp;Each artwork is a heartfelt homage to her subjects, inviting viewers to find new meanings in the shared narratives and to celebrate the profound beauty and significance inherent in their stories. </span></p><p class="c15"><span class="c9">The artist &nbsp;aims to speak to individuals with similar experiences, recognizing that while the contexts of our lives may vary infinitely, there are shared threads of resilience and identity that connect us all.</span></p><p class="c0 c2"><span class="c10"></span></p></td></tr></table><p class="c0 c19"><span class="c18">&nbsp;</span></p><a id="t.3bec4d6f24616fac9f5598b913070d7136fed0e6"></a><a id="t.1"></a><table class="c49"><tr class="c57"><td class="c16 c28" colspan="1" rowspan="1"><p class="c0 c2"><span class="c3"></span></p></td><td class="c4 c28" colspan="1" rowspan="1"><p class="c0"><span class="c21">REQUIRED</span><span class="c10">: 2 -5 Images of your final artwork/s installed in the Degree show Exhibitions as JPEG&rsquo;s, pasted below, one image per box.</span></p></td><td class="c8 c20" colspan="1" rowspan="1"><p class="c0"><span class="c21">REQUIRED</span><span class="c10">: title, size, media, dimensions</span></p><p class="c0"><span class="c41 c18">Required</span><span class="c10">: no more than 150 words per box to describe any technical, process and/or research information associated with each of your works </span></p><p class="c0 c2"><span class="c3"></span></p></td></tr><tr class="c42"><td class="c16" colspan="1" rowspan="1"><p class="c0"><span class="c3">1 </span></p></td><td class="c4" colspan="1" rowspan="1"><p class="c23 c2"><span class="c1"></span></p><p class="c23 c2"><span class="c1"></span></p><p class="c2 c23"><span class="c1"></span></p><p class="c50"><span style="overflow: hidden; display: inline-block; margin: 0.00px 0.00px; border: 0.00px solid #000000; transform: rotate(0.00rad) translateZ(0px); -webkit-transform: rotate(0.00rad) translateZ(0px); width: 543.50px; height: 364.38px;"><img alt="" src="images/image12.png" style="width: 543.50px; height: 364.38px; margin-left: 0.00px; margin-top: 0.00px; transform: rotate(0.00rad) translateZ(0px); -webkit-transform: rotate(0.00rad) translateZ(0px);" title=""></span></p></td><td class="c8" colspan="1" rowspan="1"><p class="c0"><span class="c29">It&rsquo;s Getting Cold and I&rsquo;m Far From </span></p><p class="c0"><span class="c29">Home, </span><span class="c7">2024.</span><span class="c6"><br>122x142cm (x2)</span></p><p class="c0"><span class="c6">Oil on canvas</span></p><p class="c0"><span class="c6">series</span></p><p class="c0 c2"><span class="c6"></span></p><p class="c0"><span class="c6">This work is an homage to my family&#39;s migration journey from Colombia to Spain, and to those family members who remained behind, as well as those we lost and could not bid farewell to, separated by an ocean.</span></p><p class="c0 c2"><span class="c6"></span></p><p class="c0"><span class="c6">The way the paintings are hung represents the chronological progression of the works. &quot;It was this before, and this ended up as this.&quot; If I were to add a third painting to the series, depicting my move to London alone, it would be hung lower than the second painting, continuing the downward progression and deepening the narrative of change and separation.</span></p><p class="c0 c2"><span class="c6"></span></p><p class="c0"><span class="c6">I chose the &nbsp;background colours of the second painting to match the Colombian flag.</span></p></td></tr><tr class="c53"><td class="c16" colspan="1" rowspan="1"><p class="c0"><span class="c3">2</span></p></td><td class="c4" colspan="1" rowspan="1"><p class="c0 c2"><span class="c1"></span></p><p class="c0 c2"><span class="c1"></span></p><p class="c0 c2"><span class="c1"></span></p><p class="c0"><span style="overflow: hidden; display: inline-block; margin: 0.00px 0.00px; border: 0.00px solid #000000; transform: rotate(0.00rad) translateZ(0px); -webkit-transform: rotate(0.00rad) translateZ(0px); width: 551.02px; height: 434.04px;"><img alt="" src="images/image7.png" style="width: 551.02px; height: 434.04px; margin-left: 0.00px; margin-top: 0.00px; transform: rotate(0.00rad) translateZ(0px); -webkit-transform: rotate(0.00rad) translateZ(0px);" title=""></span></p></td><td class="c8" colspan="1" rowspan="1"><p class="c0 c2"><span class="c3"></span></p><p class="c0"><span class="c29">It&rsquo;s Getting Cold</span><span class="c7">, 2024.</span><span class="c18 c40"><br></span><span class="c6">122x142cm</span></p><p class="c0"><span class="c18 c40">Oil on canvas<br></span><span class="c6">(1 of 2)</span></p><p class="c0 c2"><span class="c3"></span></p><p class="c0"><span class="c3">This first painting echoes Da Vinci&#39;s &quot;The Last Supper&quot; in its composition and undertone. Characters gather around a table, celebrating, yet shadowed by a premonition. Unlike betrayal, it is the vision of an uncertain future that haunts them, a future without their present companions. </span></p><p class="c0 c2"><span class="c3"></span></p><p class="c0"><span class="c3">Figures facing right seem to peer into the adjacent painting, foreseeing the chilling emptiness that awaits. Every chair is occupied, with even a shortage for all present, hinting at a recurring motif to be revealed in the next painting. </span></p><p class="c0 c2"><span class="c3"></span></p><p class="c0"><span class="c3">The festive yet foreboding scene encapsulates a bitter narrative of togetherness tainted by the cold grip of impending solitude.</span></p></td></tr><tr class="c59"><td class="c16" colspan="1" rowspan="1"><p class="c0"><span class="c3">3</span></p></td><td class="c4" colspan="1" rowspan="1"><p class="c0"><span style="overflow: hidden; display: inline-block; margin: 0.00px 0.00px; border: 0.00px solid #000000; transform: rotate(0.00rad) translateZ(0px); -webkit-transform: rotate(0.00rad) translateZ(0px); width: 552.50px; height: 435.20px;"><img alt="" src="images/image4.png" style="width: 552.50px; height: 435.20px; margin-left: 0.00px; margin-top: 0.00px; transform: rotate(0.00rad) translateZ(0px); -webkit-transform: rotate(0.00rad) translateZ(0px);" title=""></span></p></td><td class="c8" colspan="1" rowspan="1"><p class="c0"><span class="c29 c34">&nbsp;</span></p><p class="c0 c2"><span class="c29 c34"></span></p><p class="c0"><span class="c29">I&rsquo;m Far From Home, </span><span class="c36">2024.</span><span class="c18"><br></span><span class="c3">122x142cm</span></p><p class="c0"><span class="c18">Oil on canvas<br></span><span class="c3">(2 of 2)</span></p><p class="c0 c2"><span class="c3"></span></p><p class="c0 c2"><span class="c3"></span></p><p class="c0"><span class="c3">In this second painting, absence resounds louder than presence. Only four remain in their new home, a stark contrast to the bustling scene before. </span></p><p class="c0 c2"><span class="c3"></span></p><p class="c0"><span class="c3">Once more, the table&mdash;larger now, though serving fewer&mdash;anchors the piece, its surrounding chairs a connecting bond between all characters and their stories.</span></p><p class="c0"><span class="c3">An extra chair waits at the table, a silent invitation for my return, always saving me a seat. To the far left, a stack of unused chairs symbolizes the void left by missing loved ones. <br><br>These chairs, though empty, are kept in hope, yearning for a reunion that may one day fill the room again..</span></p></td></tr><tr class="c11"><td class="c16" colspan="1" rowspan="1"><p class="c0"><span class="c3">4</span></p></td><td class="c4" colspan="1" rowspan="1"><p class="c0"><span style="overflow: hidden; display: inline-block; margin: 0.00px 0.00px; border: 0.00px solid #000000; transform: rotate(0.00rad) translateZ(0px); -webkit-transform: rotate(0.00rad) translateZ(0px); width: 504.00px; height: 378.00px;"><img alt="" src="images/image8.jpg" style="width: 504.00px; height: 378.00px; margin-left: 0.00px; margin-top: 0.00px; transform: rotate(0.00rad) translateZ(0px); -webkit-transform: rotate(0.00rad) translateZ(0px);" title=""></span></p></td><td class="c8" colspan="1" rowspan="1"><p class="c0 c2"><span class="c3"></span></p><p class="c0 c2"><span class="c3"></span></p><p class="c0"><span class="c3">I installed my work in room D205, with the help of my peers with whom I am exhibiting. Together, we worked diligently to ensure the room and others were neat for the show, collaborating on curating and installation.</span></p><p class="c0 c2"><span class="c3"></span></p><p class="c0"><span class="c3">This experience allowed me to connect with fellow coursemates, many of whom I hadn&#39;t interacted with before, and to identify the creators of works I&#39;d admired at the previous SPG show. </span></p><p class="c0 c2"><span class="c3"></span></p><p class="c0"><span class="c3">The process was smooth and rewarding, one I&#39;d gladly repeat a thousand times.</span></p></td></tr><tr class="c11"><td class="c16" colspan="1" rowspan="1"><p class="c0"><span class="c3">5</span></p></td><td class="c4" colspan="1" rowspan="1"><p class="c0 c2"><span class="c3"></span></p></td><td class="c8" colspan="1" rowspan="1"><p class="c0 c2"><span class="c3"></span></p></td></tr><tr class="c11"><td class="c16 c28" colspan="1" rowspan="1"><p class="c0 c2"><span class="c3"></span></p></td><td class="c4 c28" colspan="1" rowspan="1"><p class="c0"><span class="c21">REQUIRED</span><span class="c10">: 10 -15 Images of your artwork as JPEG&rsquo;s, pasted below, one image per box. As many resolved artworks as possible from all of Unit 10, but can include sketches, process and experiments. If work is video or audio, include a still below, and add a link to work on the right. &nbsp;</span></p></td><td class="c8 c20" colspan="1" rowspan="1"><p class="c0"><span class="c21">REQUIRED</span><span class="c10">: title, size, media, dimensions</span></p><p class="c0"><span class="c18 c41">Required</span><span class="c10">: no more than 150 words per box to describe any technical, process and/or research information associated with each of your works </span></p><p class="c0 c2"><span class="c10"></span></p><ul class="c48 lst-kix_list_1-0 start"><li class="c2 c44 li-bullet-0"><span class="c18 c34 c40 c46 c55"></span></li></ul><p class="c0 c2"><span class="c10"></span></p></td></tr><tr class="c38"><td class="c16" colspan="1" rowspan="1"><p class="c0"><span class="c3">1</span></p></td><td class="c4" colspan="1" rowspan="1"><p class="c0"><span style="overflow: hidden; display: inline-block; margin: 0.00px 0.00px; border: 0.00px solid #000000; transform: rotate(0.00rad) translateZ(0px); -webkit-transform: rotate(0.00rad) translateZ(0px); width: 549.50px; height: 432.84px;"><img alt="" src="images/image4.png" style="width: 549.50px; height: 432.84px; margin-left: 0.00px; margin-top: 0.00px; transform: rotate(0.00rad) translateZ(0px); -webkit-transform: rotate(0.00rad) translateZ(0px);" title=""></span></p></td><td class="c8" colspan="1" rowspan="1"><p class="c0 c2"><span class="c3"></span></p><p class="c0"><span class="c3">Each character&#39;s body language, expressions, and colors in my paintings convey their unique stories and emotions.</span></p><p class="c15"><span class="c3">My grandpa faces the viewer with a mix of anger and sadness, his hands on his waist and his stance solid, almost daring. This posture reflects a resigned yet determined attitude.</span></p><p class="c15"><span class="c3">My brother&#39;s character, depicted with a blend of very dark and light colors, turns away from the past (the other painting). This symbolizes his effort to move on and adapt, despite the deep sadness he harbors for his homeland.</span></p><p class="c15"><span class="c3">My grandma is seated and making Arepas, a traditional Colombian dish she prepares for us regularly. Her position signifies her dedication to raising my brother, me, and her children, including my mother, highlighting her lifelong journey of care and nurturing.</span></p><p class="c15"><span class="c3">My mother, depicted in almost fantastical colors, is shown as a giver, always attentive to others&#39; needs, offering and preparing. Her strength is represented through her vibrant portrayal, emphasizing her pivotal role in my life.</span></p><p class="c0 c2"><span class="c3"></span></p></td></tr><tr class="c11"><td class="c16" colspan="1" rowspan="1"><p class="c0"><span class="c3">2</span></p></td><td class="c4" colspan="1" rowspan="1"><p class="c0"><span style="overflow: hidden; display: inline-block; margin: 0.00px 0.00px; border: 0.00px solid #000000; transform: rotate(0.00rad) translateZ(0px); -webkit-transform: rotate(0.00rad) translateZ(0px); width: 506.00px; height: 506.67px;"><img alt="" src="images/image2.gif" style="width: 506.00px; height: 506.67px; margin-left: 0.00px; margin-top: 0.00px; transform: rotate(0.00rad) translateZ(0px); -webkit-transform: rotate(0.00rad) translateZ(0px);" title=""></span></p></td><td class="c8" colspan="1" rowspan="1"><p class="c0 c2"><span class="c3"></span></p><p class="c0 c2"><span class="c3"></span></p><p class="c0 c2"><span class="c3"></span></p><p class="c0 c2"><span class="c3"></span></p><p class="c0"><span class="c3">In the spirit of Gaston Bachelard&rsquo;s &quot;Poetics of Space,&quot; it explores the intimate spaces of memory and absence, weaving the essence of home and the longing for what was left behind. The painting process involves layering memories with family photographs, blending traditional oil techniques with digital mediums.<br><br>In this case, the photographs were taken by me on my last visit to Spain, and I collaged different parts of them to create the composition.</span></p></td></tr><tr class="c52"><td class="c16" colspan="1" rowspan="1"><p class="c0"><span class="c3">3</span></p></td><td class="c4" colspan="1" rowspan="1"><p class="c0"><span style="overflow: hidden; display: inline-block; margin: 0.00px 0.00px; border: 0.00px solid #000000; transform: rotate(0.00rad) translateZ(0px); -webkit-transform: rotate(0.00rad) translateZ(0px); width: 548.58px; height: 387.04px;"><img alt="" src="images/image13.png" style="width: 548.58px; height: 387.04px; margin-left: 0.00px; margin-top: 0.00px; transform: rotate(0.00rad) translateZ(0px); -webkit-transform: rotate(0.00rad) translateZ(0px);" title=""></span></p></td><td class="c8" colspan="1" rowspan="1"><p class="c0 c2"><span class="c32 c7"></span></p><p class="c0 c2"><span class="c7 c32"></span></p><p class="c0 c2"><span class="c32 c7"></span></p><p class="c0"><span class="c17">Then, based on a digital collage of photographs, I created this digital drawing by blocking proportions, repositioning characters, and crafting new shadows and lights according to their new placements. At this stage, I selected the color palette, setting the tone for the painting. I also included intricate tiling decorations on the walls, a hallmark of the south of Spain. </span></p><p class="c0 c2"><span class="c17"></span></p><p class="c0"><span class="c17">Initially, I aimed for pastel colors and undefined shapes, creating a subtle and soft effect, which you will see in the early stages on the canvas. I referenced Douglas Cantor&rsquo;s painting technique and colour palette to come up with it. However, I decided to shift to more eye-catching, expressive tones to convey greater force. </span></p><p class="c0 c2"><span class="c17"></span></p><p class="c0"><span class="c17">This is the second painting of the series, yet it was the first one to be created.</span></p></td></tr><tr class="c13"><td class="c16" colspan="1" rowspan="1"><p class="c0"><span class="c3">4</span></p></td><td class="c4" colspan="1" rowspan="1"><p class="c0"><span style="overflow: hidden; display: inline-block; margin: 0.00px 0.00px; border: 0.00px solid #000000; transform: rotate(0.00rad) translateZ(0px); -webkit-transform: rotate(0.00rad) translateZ(0px); width: 505.00px; height: 379.00px;"><img alt="" src="images/image15.jpg" style="width: 505.00px; height: 379.00px; margin-left: 0.00px; margin-top: 0.00px; transform: rotate(0.00rad) translateZ(0px); -webkit-transform: rotate(0.00rad) translateZ(0px);" title=""></span></p></td><td class="c8" colspan="1" rowspan="1"><p class="c0 c2"><span class="c1"></span></p><p class="c0 c2"><span class="c1"></span></p><p class="c0"><span class="c3">Using the digital sketch and collage as a guide, I translated the composition onto the canvas. </span></p><p class="c0 c2"><span class="c3"></span></p><p class="c0"><span class="c3">I chose an orange underpainting to represent the city of Sevilla, where my family lives in Spain. This color embodies Sevilla&#39;s essence.</span></p><p class="c0 c2"><span class="c3"></span></p><p class="c0"><span class="c3">In contrast, I outlined and shaded everything in green, the color I used for the underpainting of the other painting. Green, for me, represents Colombia, a country where rain nourishes abundant, tropical nature. This juxtaposition of colors bridges the personal and geographical connections within my work.<br><br>The orange underpainting is fully visible on the entire floor in the finished painting.</span></p></td></tr><tr class="c27"><td class="c16" colspan="1" rowspan="1"><p class="c0"><span class="c3">5</span></p></td><td class="c4" colspan="1" rowspan="1"><p class="c0"><span style="overflow: hidden; display: inline-block; margin: 0.00px 0.00px; border: 0.00px solid #000000; transform: rotate(0.00rad) translateZ(0px); -webkit-transform: rotate(0.00rad) translateZ(0px); width: 409.00px; height: 544.00px;"><img alt="" src="images/image1.jpg" style="width: 545.00px; height: 409.05px; margin-left: -68.00px; margin-top: 68.40px; transform: rotate(-1.57rad) translateZ(0px); -webkit-transform: rotate(-1.57rad) translateZ(0px);" title=""></span></p></td><td class="c8" colspan="1" rowspan="1"><p class="c0 c2"><span class="c12"></span></p><p class="c0 c2"><span class="c12"></span></p><p class="c0 c2"><span class="c12"></span></p><p class="c0"><span class="c3">The door arch in the left background is intentionally left undefined, symbolizing unfinished business. It connects to the half-open door in the other painting, creating a link between the two works and suggesting continuity and unresolved narratives.</span></p><p class="c0 c2"><span class="c3"></span></p><p class="c0"><span class="c3">There are also beef empanadas served on the table, another Colombian dish. My mother is the one that always makes them, and she makes sure everything is set for us. </span></p><p class="c0"><span class="c3">This dish takes a remarkably long time to make from beginning to end, which reflects her commitment to her family and her role as a provider and nourisher. </span></p><p class="c0 c2"><span class="c3"></span></p><p class="c0"><span class="c3">There are also 4 shots, as if they had been taken from the tray of the other painting. Cheer for what once was.</span></p></td></tr><tr class="c11"><td class="c16" colspan="1" rowspan="1"><p class="c0"><span class="c3">6</span></p></td><td class="c4" colspan="1" rowspan="1"><p class="c0"><span style="overflow: hidden; display: inline-block; margin: 0.00px 0.00px; border: 0.00px solid #000000; transform: rotate(0.00rad) translateZ(0px); -webkit-transform: rotate(0.00rad) translateZ(0px); width: 505.00px; height: 379.00px;"><img alt="" src="images/image11.jpg" style="width: 505.00px; height: 379.00px; margin-left: 0.00px; margin-top: 0.00px; transform: rotate(0.00rad) translateZ(0px); -webkit-transform: rotate(0.00rad) translateZ(0px);" title=""></span></p></td><td class="c8" colspan="1" rowspan="1"><p class="c0 c2"><span class="c12"></span></p><p class="c0"><span class="c3">Here is a picture that illustrates my initial use of pastel and soft colors. However, I felt these colors didn&#39;t convey the strength of the emotions and stories I intended.</span></p><p class="c0 c2"><span class="c3"></span></p><p class="c0"><span class="c3">I add it, mostly, to show you what the journey of the painting went through until it became what it is now.</span></p></td></tr><tr class="c43"><td class="c16" colspan="1" rowspan="1"><p class="c0"><span class="c3">7</span></p></td><td class="c4" colspan="1" rowspan="1"><p class="c0"><span style="overflow: hidden; display: inline-block; margin: 0.00px 0.00px; border: 0.00px solid #000000; transform: rotate(0.00rad) translateZ(0px); -webkit-transform: rotate(0.00rad) translateZ(0px); width: 504.00px; height: 397.00px;"><img alt="" src="images/image7.png" style="width: 504.00px; height: 397.00px; margin-left: 0.00px; margin-top: 0.00px; transform: rotate(0.00rad) translateZ(0px); -webkit-transform: rotate(0.00rad) translateZ(0px);" title=""></span></p></td><td class="c8" colspan="1" rowspan="1"><p class="c0 c2"><span class="c3"></span></p><p class="c0"><span class="c3">In this painting, I included members of my family who are no longer alive, using this piece as an opportunity to remember them, allowing them to live on beyond my memories. </span></p><p class="c0 c2"><span class="c3"></span></p><p class="c0"><span class="c3">Again, the table and chairs are the brightest part of the painting, keeping them as the focal point of the scene. </span></p><p class="c0 c2"><span class="c3"></span></p><p class="c0"><span class="c3">The house in the background, depicted as a fading memory, was my aunt&#39;s house, where she raised me for a year. </span></p><p class="c0"><span class="c3">Although the numbers on the right (Mz-18, C-29) represent the address of my grandparents&#39; house, where they raised my brother and me while my mother was alone in Spain for 7 years, until she could bring us there.<br><br>I wasn&rsquo;t too experienced in painting a lot of characters in one work, most of my previous work included a singular figure in them, which urged me to seek guidance on Nichole Eisenman&rsquo;s work. My tutor suggested me to study her work, which is often filled with crowds, but with a compositional richness to it that makes them feel a quiet room.</span></p></td></tr><tr class="c35"><td class="c16" colspan="1" rowspan="1"><p class="c0"><span class="c3">8</span></p></td><td class="c4" colspan="1" rowspan="1"><p class="c0"><span style="overflow: hidden; display: inline-block; margin: 0.00px 0.00px; border: 0.00px solid #000000; transform: rotate(0.00rad) translateZ(0px); -webkit-transform: rotate(0.00rad) translateZ(0px); width: 554.55px; height: 369.04px;"><img alt="" src="images/image3.gif" style="width: 554.55px; height: 369.04px; margin-left: 0.00px; margin-top: 0.00px; transform: rotate(0.00rad) translateZ(0px); -webkit-transform: rotate(0.00rad) translateZ(0px);" title=""></span></p></td><td class="c8" colspan="1" rowspan="1"><p class="c0 c2"><span class="c3"></span></p><p class="c0 c2"><span class="c3"></span></p><p class="c0"><span class="c3">To create the composition of this piece, I used a mix of old family photographs sent by my aunt, those we brought to Spain, and pictures I took during my last visit to Colombia last year. </span></p><p class="c0 c2"><span class="c3"></span></p><p class="c0"><span class="c3">I combined elements from these photos to form this collage.</span></p><p class="c0 c2"><span class="c3"></span></p><p class="c0"><span class="c3">The house and address I referenced earlier are depicted here. </span></p><p class="c0 c2"><span class="c3"></span></p><p class="c0"><span class="c3">The photos, from the 80s, 90s and early 2000s, were of low quality, so I had to paint most of the faces from memory and recreate body parts that weren&rsquo;t visible. </span></p><p class="c0 c2"><span class="c3"></span></p><p class="c0"><span class="c3">This process was an excellent exercise in painting from reference, memory, and imagination.</span></p><p class="c0 c2"><span class="c3"></span></p><p class="c0"><span class="c3">This process was highly inspired by Meenakashi Ghadial&rsquo;s paintings, which also uses family pictures to create a different narrative.</span></p></td></tr><tr class="c25"><td class="c16" colspan="1" rowspan="1"><p class="c0"><span class="c3">9</span></p></td><td class="c4" colspan="1" rowspan="1"><p class="c0"><span style="overflow: hidden; display: inline-block; margin: 0.00px 0.00px; border: 0.00px solid #000000; transform: rotate(0.00rad) translateZ(0px); -webkit-transform: rotate(0.00rad) translateZ(0px); width: 550.50px; height: 413.16px;"><img alt="" src="images/image5.jpg" style="width: 550.50px; height: 413.16px; margin-left: 0.00px; margin-top: 0.00px; transform: rotate(0.00rad) translateZ(0px); -webkit-transform: rotate(0.00rad) translateZ(0px);" title=""></span></p></td><td class="c8" colspan="1" rowspan="1"><p class="c0 c2"><span class="c3"></span></p><p class="c0 c2"><span class="c3"></span></p><p class="c0 c2"><span class="c3"></span></p><p class="c0 c2"><span class="c3"></span></p><p class="c0"><span class="c3">Similar to my other work, I used the collage as a reference and sketched it onto the canvas. </span></p><p class="c0 c2"><span class="c3"></span></p><p class="c0"><span class="c3">The green underpainting, though less visible here than in the other piece, influenced the color palette significantly. Its contrast added warmth to the final composition. </span></p><p class="c0 c2"><span class="c3"></span></p><p class="c0 c2"><span class="c3"></span></p></td></tr><tr class="c33"><td class="c16" colspan="1" rowspan="1"><p class="c0"><span class="c3">11</span></p></td><td class="c4" colspan="1" rowspan="1"><p class="c0"><span style="overflow: hidden; display: inline-block; margin: 0.00px 0.00px; border: 0.00px solid #000000; transform: rotate(0.00rad) translateZ(0px); -webkit-transform: rotate(0.00rad) translateZ(0px); width: 548.52px; height: 432.04px;"><img alt="" src="images/image10.jpg" style="width: 761.00px; height: 568.68px; margin-left: -78.36px; margin-top: -68.33px; transform: rotate(0.00rad) translateZ(0px); -webkit-transform: rotate(0.00rad) translateZ(0px);" title=""></span></p></td><td class="c8" colspan="1" rowspan="1"><p class="c0 c2"><span class="c12"></span></p><p class="c0 c2"><span class="c12"></span></p><p class="c0 c2"><span class="c12"></span></p><p class="c0"><span class="c3">I wanted to include this picture because, due to the closure of the studios well before our deadline, I had to take my paintings home and complete them there. </span></p><p class="c0 c2"><span class="c3"></span></p><p class="c0"><span class="c3">Unfortunately, the lighting at home was poor, causing the colors to appear nothing like what I had planned. </span></p><p class="c0 c2"><span class="c3"></span></p><p class="c0"><span class="c3">At this stage, I was disheartened and considered scrapping the piece altogether. However, I persevered and continued working on it. I&#39;m thrilled that I made the decision to persist, as the outcome exceeded my expectations.</span></p></td></tr><tr class="c47"><td class="c16" colspan="1" rowspan="1"><p class="c0"><span class="c3">12</span></p></td><td class="c4" colspan="1" rowspan="1"><p class="c0"><span style="overflow: hidden; display: inline-block; margin: 0.00px 0.00px; border: 0.00px solid #000000; transform: rotate(0.00rad) translateZ(0px); -webkit-transform: rotate(0.00rad) translateZ(0px); width: 547.56px; height: 365.04px;"><img alt="" src="images/image9.gif" style="width: 547.56px; height: 365.04px; margin-left: 0.00px; margin-top: 0.00px; transform: rotate(0.00rad) translateZ(0px); -webkit-transform: rotate(0.00rad) translateZ(0px);" title=""></span></p></td><td class="c8" colspan="1" rowspan="1"><p class="c0 c2"><span class="c3"></span></p><p class="c0 c2"><span class="c3"></span></p><p class="c0"><span class="c3">These two paintings are a culmination of my work with our family archival pictures. </span></p><p class="c0 c2"><span class="c3"></span></p><p class="c0"><span class="c3">It&#39;s important to note that they represent only a small compilation from the hundreds of images I sifted through to select the final ones. </span></p><p class="c0 c2"><span class="c3"></span></p><p class="c0"><span class="c3">Here, I share a few images and compositions where I experimented with different elements and pictures, attempting to craft a cohesive narrative that ultimately didn&#39;t make the cut.</span></p><p class="c0 c2"><span class="c3"></span></p><p class="c0"><span class="c3">Also, at this stage I had planned to include myself in one of these paintings, but I decided to focus it on my family and act as a narrator only.</span></p></td></tr><tr class="c11"><td class="c16" colspan="1" rowspan="1"><p class="c0"><span class="c3">13</span></p></td><td class="c4" colspan="1" rowspan="1"><p class="c0"><span style="overflow: hidden; display: inline-block; margin: 0.00px 0.00px; border: 0.00px solid #000000; transform: rotate(0.00rad) translateZ(0px); -webkit-transform: rotate(0.00rad) translateZ(0px); width: 420.00px; height: 504.00px;"><img alt="" src="images/image14.jpg" style="width: 420.00px; height: 504.00px; margin-left: 0.00px; margin-top: 0.00px; transform: rotate(0.00rad) translateZ(0px); -webkit-transform: rotate(0.00rad) translateZ(0px);" title=""></span></p></td><td class="c8" colspan="1" rowspan="1"><p class="c0"><span class="c30 c46">Portrait of Patricia I</span><span class="c3">, 2024.</span></p><p class="c0"><span class="c3">Oil on canvas</span></p><p class="c0"><span class="c3">60x80cm</span></p><p class="c0 c2"><span class="c12"></span></p><p class="c0"><span class="c3">Furthermore, I continued my live-painting sessions with my friends, inviting them to my studio space in Camberwell and having them pose for me. </span></p><p class="c0 c2"><span class="c3"></span></p><p class="c0"><span class="c3">This aspect of my practice is dedicated to portraying queer and/or people of color in my life, striving to provide them with the representation that has historically been lacking in art.</span></p><p class="c0 c2"><span class="c3"></span></p><p class="c0"><span class="c3">I see this process as a valuable moment of connection between myself and the person I&#39;m painting. It&#39;s not easy to be vulnerable and allow someone to observe you so closely, granting them the freedom to portray you as they perceive you. I was highly inspired by Jennifer Packer&rsquo;s work, who often creates live painting of black women exclusively, to honour them among a crowd. </span></p><p class="c0 c2"><span class="c3"></span></p><p class="c0"><span class="c3">In my opinion, it&#39;s an act of generosity on their part.</span></p></td></tr><tr class="c11"><td class="c16" colspan="1" rowspan="1"><p class="c0"><span class="c3">14</span></p></td><td class="c4" colspan="1" rowspan="1"><p class="c0"><span style="overflow: hidden; display: inline-block; margin: 0.00px 0.00px; border: 0.00px solid #000000; transform: rotate(0.00rad) translateZ(0px); -webkit-transform: rotate(0.00rad) translateZ(0px); width: 506.00px; height: 564.00px;"><img alt="" src="images/image6.png" style="width: 506.00px; height: 564.00px; margin-left: 0.00px; margin-top: 0.00px; transform: rotate(0.00rad) translateZ(0px); -webkit-transform: rotate(0.00rad) translateZ(0px);" title=""></span></p></td><td class="c8" colspan="1" rowspan="1"><p class="c0"><span class="c30 c46">Portrait of Patricia II</span><span class="c3">, 2024.</span></p><p class="c0"><span class="c3">Oil on canvas</span></p><p class="c0"><span class="c3">60x80cm</span></p><p class="c0 c2"><span class="c3"></span></p><p class="c15"><span class="c3">These two paintings depict my friend Patricia. In my first year (2020), I painted her as part of a series titled &quot;People of Colour Around You,&quot; which consisted of small watercolor paintings in a sketchbook. This series was inspired by the observation that everyone working at the restaurant where I was employed (my first workplace in the UK) was a person of color, except for the managers. That&#39;s how Patricia and I met.</span></p><p class="c15"><span class="c3">This painting was completed before the one above, approximately three hours later. Patricia&#39;s pose and her avoidance of my gaze in this painting indicate that it was a significant step for her to pose for me.</span></p><p class="c15"><span class="c3">&nbsp;However, in the subsequent painting, you can see her growing more comfortable and confident over time.</span></p><p class="c15"><span class="c3">Thank you Patricia.</span></p><p class="c0 c2"><span class="c3"></span></p></td></tr><tr class="c11"><td class="c16" colspan="1" rowspan="1"><p class="c0 c2"><span class="c3"></span></p></td><td class="c4" colspan="1" rowspan="1"><p class="c0"><span class="c1">THE END</span></p></td><td class="c8" colspan="1" rowspan="1"><p class="c0"><span class="c30 c34 c46">2024</span></p></td></tr></table><p class="c0 c2"><span class="c3"></span></p><p class="c24 c2"><span class="c1"></span></p><p class="c24 c2"><span class="c1"></span></p><p class="c2 c24"><span class="c1"></span></p><div><p class="c2 c22"><span class="c31"></span></p></div></body></html>
